\begin{abstract}
Niu's recent work on the Sidon-extension problem isolates the two
four-point Sidon sets
\[
 A=\{0,1,3,11\},\qquad B=\{0,1,4,11\}
\]
as apparent minimal obstructions to extension to perfect difference sets.
The computational evidence in arXiv:2604.25214 includes a Singer
affine-orbit check through prime powers \(q\leq 317\), while a complete
proof was left as an open problem.  We prove the Singer part for every
prime power \(q\).  If \(D_q\subseteq \Z_{q^2+q+1}\) is the canonical
Singer trace difference set, then \(D_q\) contains no affine image of
\(A\) or \(B\).  The proof reduces affine containment to a rank-two
condition on four powers \(1,w,w^a,w^b\) in \(\F_{q^3}\), and then rules
out the two resulting cubic identities by elementary polynomial
division.  Combining this with the Huang--Schmidt classification of
cyclic projective planes below order \(41\), we obtain unconditional
non-containment for all cyclic planar difference sets of order
\(q<41\).  Finally we formulate the first unresolved multiplier-orbit
frontier, \(q=41\), as an explicit finite exact-cover system on the
\(574\) nonzero Frobenius orbits in \(\Z_{1723}\).  This is a boundary
formulation only: the non-Singer multiplier problem for \(q\geq 41\)
remains open here.
\end{abstract}

