\section{Introduction}

A finite set \(S\subset \Z\) is a Sidon set if its nonzero pairwise
differences are distinct.  A planar difference set of order \(q\) in a
cyclic group \(G\) of order
\[
 v=q^2+q+1
\]
is a subset \(D\subseteq G\) of size \(q+1\) such that every nonzero
element of \(G\) has a unique representation \(d-d'\) with
\(d,d'\in D\).  Equivalently, in the integral group ring,
\[
 DD^{(-1)}=q+G.
\]
This is the cyclic version of a perfect difference set of size \(q+1\):
with Niu's notation \(n=q+1\), the modulus is
\(n^2-n+1=q^2+q+1\).

Erd\H{o}s asked whether every finite Sidon set extends to a finite
perfect difference set.  Alexeev and Mixon disproved this conjecture by
showing that \(\{1,2,4,8,13\}\) is forbidden, and also revisited an
earlier example of Hall \cite{Hall,AlexeevMixon}.  Niu subsequently
proposed that the smallest forbidden size is \(4\), giving strong
evidence for the two sets
\[
 A=\{0,1,3,11\},\qquad B=\{0,1,4,11\}.
\]
In particular, Niu's arXiv:2604.25214 reports that these two patterns
do not occur in the Singer affine-orbit model for prime powers
\(q\leq 317\), and records the need for a complete proof, for instance
by a polarity argument or by a multiplier descent \cite{Niu}.

The purpose of this note is to separate the Singer obstruction from the
harder cyclic-plane uniqueness problem.  The Singer obstruction admits a
short proof for all \(q\).  Let \(K=\F_q\), let \(F=\F_{q^3}\), and let
\(\alpha\) generate \(F^\times\).  The canonical Singer line is
\[
 D_q=\{\,i\in \Z_{q^2+q+1}:\Tr_{F/K}(\alpha^i)=0\,\}.
\]
We show that if an affine copy \(t+u\{0,1,a,b\}\) is contained in
\(D_q\), with \(u\) a unit modulo \(q^2+q+1\), then
\[
 \dim_K\Span_K\{1,w,w^a,w^b\}\leq 2,\qquad w=\alpha^u.
\]
For \(A\), this forces an irreducible cubic \(x^3-rx-s\) whose
reduction of \(x^{11}\) gives \(s(4r^3+s^2)=0\); this immediately
implies reducibility.  For \(B\), the relation \(w^4\in\Span_K\{1,w\}\)
forces a cubic \(x^3-ax^2+a^2x-c\), and the \(x^2\)-coefficient of
\(x^{11}\) gives
\[
 \left(\frac{c}{a^3}\right)^3
 -2\left(\frac{c}{a^3}\right)^2
 +3\left(\frac{c}{a^3}\right)-1=0.
\]
The identity
\[
 (1-y)^3-(1-y)^2+(1-y)-y
 =-(y^3-2y^2+3y-1)
\]
then exhibits a \(K\)-rational root of the cubic, again contradicting
irreducibility.

For arbitrary cyclic planar difference sets the question is different.
The classical multiplier theorem, recorded by Huang and Schmidt, says
that if \(q=p^f\), then every cyclic planar difference set of order
\(q\) is equivalent to one fixed by the multiplier \(p\)
\cite[Result 4]{HuangSchmidt}.  Huang and Schmidt also prove that every
cyclic projective plane of order at most \(37\) is Desarguesian
\cite[Theorem 28]{HuangSchmidt}.  Hence every cyclic planar difference
set of order \(q<41\) is Singer-equivalent, and the all-\(q\) Singer
obstruction below gives unconditional non-containment in this range.  The
present cyclic-plane consequence stops at this classification boundary;
for \(q\geq 41\), the non-Singer multiplier problem remains open.

The first multiplier-orbit problem not disposed of by this classification
is \(q=41\), where \(v=1723\) is prime and the \(41\)-orbits on
\(\Z_v^\times\) all have length \(3\).  A normalized difference set is a
union of exactly \(14\) such orbits.  We formulate the exact quadratic
binary system whose solutions are precisely the normalized cyclic planar
difference sets, together with the forced orbit constraints coming from
an affine copy of \(A\) or \(B\).  This final finite system is used only
to mark the remaining frontier addressed in the discussion.

The novelty is correspondingly narrow.  The trace-rank criterion is
packaged as the finite-field interface needed for this proof; the new
proof content is the pair of elementary cubic contradictions for \(A\)
and \(B\); and the \(q=41\) orbit system is made explicit as the first
multiplier frontier, not as a certified infeasibility result or a
benchmark study.

\section{Preliminaries}

\subsection*{Cyclic planar difference sets}

Throughout, all cyclic groups are written additively.  If \(G=\Z_v\) and
\(D\subseteq G\), then
\[
 D^{(-1)}=\{-d:d\in D\}.
\]
We identify \(D\) with \(\sum_{d\in D}d\in \Z[G]\).  A subset
\(D\subseteq \Z_v\) is a cyclic planar difference set of order \(q\) if
\[
 v=q^2+q+1,\qquad |D|=q+1,
\]
and
\[
 DD^{(-1)}=q+\Z_v.
\]
Equivalently, every nonzero residue of \(\Z_v\) occurs exactly once as
an ordered difference \(d-d'\), \(d,d'\in D\), \(d\ne d'\).

Two cyclic planar difference sets in \(\Z_v\) are equivalent if one is
obtained from the other by a translation and a group automorphism, i.e.
by a map
\[
 x\longmapsto c+ux,\qquad c\in \Z_v,\quad u\in \Z_v^\times.
\]
For a set \(S\subset \Z\), an affine image of \(S\) in \(\Z_v\) means
\[
 t+uS=\{t+us:s\in S\}\subseteq \Z_v
\]
with \(u\in\Z_v^\times\).  This is the notion relevant to equivalence of
cyclic difference sets: if \(E=c+uD\), then \(E\) contains an affine copy
of \(S\) if and only if \(D\) does.  Indeed, if \(E\) contains
\(t+rS\), then \(D\) contains
\[
 u^{-1}(t-c)+u^{-1}rS,
\]
and the converse follows by applying the affine map \(x\mapsto c+ux\).

\subsection*{The Singer trace construction}

Let \(K=\F_q\), \(F=\F_{q^3}\), and let \(\alpha\) be a generator of
\(F^\times\).  Put
\[
 v=\frac{q^3-1}{q-1}=q^2+q+1.
\]
Then \(\alpha^v\in K^\times\).  Since multiplication by an element of
\(K^\times\) preserves trace zero, the set
\[
 D_q=\{\,i\in \Z_v:\Tr_{F/K}(\alpha^i)=0\,\}
\]
is well-defined.  It has size \(q+1\): the trace-zero hyperplane in
\(F\) has \(q^2\) elements, \(q^2-1\) of them nonzero, and the nonzero
elements are partitioned into \(K^\times\)-orbits of size \(q-1\).
Singer's construction says that \(D_q\) is a cyclic planar difference
set of order \(q\), and every difference set arising from a line in
\(\operatorname{PG}(2,q)\) is equivalent to it \cite{Singer}.

We will use two standard facts about finite fields.  First, the trace
pairing
\[
 F\times F\longrightarrow K,\qquad (x,y)\longmapsto \Tr_{F/K}(xy)
\]
is nondegenerate.  Second, if \(w\in F\setminus K\), then \(K(w)=F\).
Indeed, \([K(w):K]\) divides \([F:K]=3\), and it is not \(1\).

\subsection*{Trace-rank interface}

\begin{lemma}[Trace-rank criterion]
\label{lem:trace-rank}
Fix a prime power \(q\).  Let \(K=\F_q\), \(F=\F_{q^3}\), let
\(\alpha\) generate \(F^\times\), put \(v=q^2+q+1\), and let
\[
 D_q=\{\,i\in \Z_v:\Tr_{F/K}(\alpha^i)=0\,\}.
\]
Let \(S=\{0,1,a,b\}\subset\Z\) and let \(u\in\Z_v^\times\).  For
\(w=\alpha^u\), one has \(w\notin K\), and there exists a translate
\(t\in\Z_v\) such that
\[
 t+uS\subseteq D_q
\]
if and only if, inside the fixed \(K\)-vector space
\(F=\F_{q^3}\),
\[
 \dim_K\Span_K\{1,w,w^a,w^b\}\leq 2.
\]
Equivalently, for a fixed \(t\), the containment \(t+uS\subseteq D_q\)
holds precisely when \(\alpha^t\) lies in the trace annihilator of this
span.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
If the integer representative of \(u\) is changed by a multiple of
\(v\), then \(w\) is multiplied by an element of \(K^\times\); the four
vectors \(1,w,w^a,w^b\) are only rescaled by nonzero elements of \(K\),
so the displayed dimension is well-defined for \(u\in\Z_v^\times\).

The condition \(u\in\Z_v^\times\) also implies \(w\notin K\).  Indeed,
\(K^\times=\langle\alpha^v\rangle\); if \(\alpha^u\in K^\times\), then
the exponent \(u\) is congruent to \(0\) modulo \(v\), contradicting
that \(u\) is a unit modulo \(v\).

For a fixed \(t\), the containment \(t+uS\subseteq D_q\) is exactly
\[
 \Tr_{F/K}(\alpha^t w^s)=0\qquad(s\in S).
\]
Thus \(\alpha^t\) annihilates
\(\Span_K\{1,w,w^a,w^b\}\) under the nondegenerate trace pairing on the
fixed field \(F\).  Conversely, if \(\alpha^t\) annihilates this span,
then the same displayed trace equations give \(t+uS\subseteq D_q\).
Since \(\dim_K F=3\), a nonzero annihilator exists if and only if the
span has dimension at most \(2\).  Every nonzero element of \(F\) is
some \(\alpha^t\), and replacing \(t\) by its class modulo \(v\) does
not change membership in \(D_q\), because \(\alpha^v\in K^\times\) and
\(K^\times\) preserves trace zero.
\end{proof}

\subsection*{Multiplier and Frobenius orbits}

Let \(q=p^f\) and \(v=q^2+q+1\).  For \(D\subseteq \Z_v\), write
\[
 D^{(p)}=\{pd:d\in D\}.
\]
The classical multiplier theorem for cyclic planar difference sets of
prime-power order, in the form recorded by Huang and Schmidt, states
that every cyclic planar difference set of order \(q=p^f\) is equivalent
to a difference set satisfying
\[
 D^{(p)}=D.
\]
Thus, after equivalence, \(D\) is a union of orbits for the map
\(x\mapsto px\) on \(\Z_v\).  We write
\[
 [x]=\{p^i x\bmod v:i\geq 0\}
\]
for such an orbit.  The exact orbit equations used below are obtained
by expanding the group-ring equation \(DD^{(-1)}=q+\Z_v\) after writing
\(D\) as a union of these Frobenius or multiplier orbits.

\section{Main results}

\begin{theorem}[Singer-affine obstruction for all prime powers]
\label{thm:singer}
Let \(q\) be a prime power, let \(v=q^2+q+1\), and let
\(\alpha\) be a generator of \(\F_{q^3}^{\times}\).  Let
\[
 D_q=\{\,i\in \Z_v:\Tr_{\F_{q^3}/\F_q}(\alpha^i)=0\,\}
\]
be a Singer trace difference set.  Then \(D_q\) contains no affine image
of
\[
 A=\{0,1,3,11\}
 \quad\text{or}\quad
 B=\{0,1,4,11\}.
\]
Consequently no Singer difference set equivalent to \(D_q\) contains an
affine image of \(A\) or \(B\).
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Let \(K=\F_q\) and \(F=\F_{q^3}\).  By
Lemma~\ref{lem:trace-rank}, any affine copy of \(A\) or \(B\) in
\(D_q\) would produce an element \(w\in F\setminus K\) satisfying the
corresponding rank condition.  We now rule out those two possibilities.

\smallskip
\noindent\emph{The set \(A=\{0,1,3,11\}\).}
Assume, for contradiction, that
\[
 \dim_K\Span_K\{1,w,w^3,w^{11}\}\leq 2
\]
for some \(w\in F\setminus K\).  Since \(1,w\) are independent, there
are \(r,s\in K\) such that
\[
 w^3=rw+s.
\]
Thus \(w\) is a root of
\[
 f(x)=x^3-rx-s.
\]
Because \(w\notin K\) and \(F/K\) has prime degree \(3\), the minimal
polynomial of \(w\) over \(K\) has degree \(3\).  Therefore this cubic
\(f\) is irreducible over \(K\), and \(\{1,w,w^2\}\) is a \(K\)-basis
of \(F\).

Reducing \(x^{11}\) modulo \(x^3-rx-s\), using \(x^3\equiv rx+s\), gives
\[
 x^{11}\equiv
 (4r^3s+s^3)x^2+(r^5+6r^2s^2)x+(r^4s+3rs^3)
 \pmod{x^3-rx-s}.
\]
Since \(w^{11}\in\Span_K\{1,w\}\), the \(x^2\)-coefficient of the
remainder must vanish:
\[
 4r^3s+s^3=0,
 \qquad\text{or equivalently}\qquad
 s(4r^3+s^2)=0.
\]
If \(s=0\), then \(f(x)=x(x^2-r)\) is reducible, contradiction.

Suppose next that \(\operatorname{char}K=2\).  Then \(4=0\), so the
same equation gives \(s^3=0\), hence \(s=0\), again a contradiction.

It remains to consider \(\operatorname{char}K\ne 2\) and \(s\ne 0\).
Then
\[
 s^2=-4r^3.
\]
In particular \(r\ne 0\), and
\[
 (-r)^3=\left(\frac{s}{2}\right)^2
\]
is a square in \(K^\times\).  Since \(K^\times\) is cyclic and cubing
does not change the parity of an exponent, \(-r\) is itself a square.
Choose \(\tau\in K\) with \(\tau^2=-r\).  Then
\[
 s^2=4\tau^6,
\]
so \(s=\pm 2\tau^3\).  If \(s=2\tau^3\), then
\[
 f(\tau)=\tau^3+\tau^2\tau-2\tau^3=0.
\]
If \(s=-2\tau^3\), then
\[
 f(-\tau)=-\tau^3-\tau^3+2\tau^3=0.
\]
In either case \(f\) has a root in \(K\), contradicting irreducibility.
This proves that the rank condition is impossible for \(A\).

\smallskip
\noindent\emph{The set \(B=\{0,1,4,11\}\).}
Assume, for contradiction, that
\[
 \dim_K\Span_K\{1,w,w^4,w^{11}\}\leq 2
\]
for some \(w\in F\setminus K\).  Write the cubic relation of \(w\) as
\[
 w^3=aw^2+bw+c,\qquad a,b,c\in K.
\]
Equivalently, \(w\) is a root of
\[
 f(x)=x^3-ax^2-bx-c.
\]
As above, \(f\) is the irreducible minimal polynomial of \(w\) over
\(K\).

Reducing \(x^4\) modulo \(f\) gives
\[
 x^4\equiv (a^2+b)x^2+(ab+c)x+ac \pmod f.
\]
Since \(w^4\in\Span_K\{1,w\}\), the \(x^2\)-coefficient is zero, so
\[
 b=-a^2.
\]
Thus
\[
 f(x)=x^3-ax^2+a^2x-c.
\]
Now reduce \(x^{11}\) modulo this cubic.  The coefficient of \(x^2\) in
the remainder is
\[
 c^3-2a^3c^2+3a^6c-a^9.
\]
Since \(w^{11}\in\Span_K\{1,w\}\), this expression is zero.  If
\(a=0\), then \(c^3=0\), so \(c=0\), and \(f(x)=x^3\) is reducible.
Hence \(a\ne0\).

Set
\[
 y=\frac{c}{a^3}.
\]
Dividing the displayed equation by \(a^9\) gives
\[
 y^3-2y^2+3y-1=0.
\]
The elementary identity
\[
 (1-y)^3-(1-y)^2+(1-y)-y
 =-(y^3-2y^2+3y-1)
\]
therefore implies that \(z=1-y\) satisfies
\[
 z^3-z^2+z-y=0.
\]
Consequently \(x=az=a(1-y)\in K\) is a root of \(f\), because
\[
 f(az)
 =a^3z^3-a^3z^2+a^3z-c
 =a^3(z^3-z^2+z-y)=0.
\]
This contradicts irreducibility.  The rank condition is impossible for
\(B\) as well.

By Lemma~\ref{lem:trace-rank}, neither affine containment can occur in
\(D_q\).  Equivalence of Singer difference sets is by affine maps
\(x\mapsto c+ux\), so the final assertion follows from the
affine-containment invariance proved in the preliminaries.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Reduction to Singer for \(q<41\)]
\label{thm:smallq}
Let \(q<41\) be a prime power, let \(v=q^2+q+1\), and let
\(D\subseteq \Z_v\) be any cyclic planar difference set of order \(q\).
Then \(D\) contains no affine image of
\[
 A=\{0,1,3,11\}
 \quad\text{or}\quad
 B=\{0,1,4,11\}.
\]
Moreover, if \(q=p^f\), every such \(D\) is equivalent to a
\(p\)-multiplier-fixed representative \(D^{(p)}=D\); for \(q<41\) this
representative is Singer-equivalent.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
The multiplier assertion is the standard multiplier theorem for cyclic
planar difference sets of prime-power order, as recorded by Huang and
Schmidt \cite[Result 4]{HuangSchmidt}: after equivalence, one may assume
\(D^{(p)}=D\).

For the non-containment statement, use the classification theorem of
Huang and Schmidt \cite[Theorem 28]{HuangSchmidt}, which says that every
cyclic projective plane of order at most \(37\) is Desarguesian.  Since
the prime powers below \(41\) are all at most \(37\), the cyclic
projective plane associated with \(D\) is Desarguesian.  The precise
bridge supplied by their Proposition~5 is that, for prime-power order \(q\),
a cyclic planar difference set not equivalent to a Singer difference set
generates a non-Desarguesian projective plane; equivalently, by
contrapositive, any cyclic planar difference set generating a
Desarguesian plane is equivalent to a Singer difference set
\cite[Proposition 5]{HuangSchmidt}.  Thus \(D\) is equivalent to a Singer
difference set.  Equivalence is affine in \(\Z_v\), so affine
containment of \(A\) or \(B\) would transfer to an affine containment in
a Singer difference set.  This is impossible by Theorem
\ref{thm:singer}.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}[The \(q=41\) multiplier-orbit exact-cover frontier]
\label{lem:q41}
Let \(q=41\), \(v=q^2+q+1=1723\), and \(G=\Z_v\).  After multiplier
normalization, every cyclic planar difference set \(D\subseteq G\) of
order \(41\) is a union of exactly \(14\) nonzero orbits
\[
 [r]=\{r,41r,41^2r\}=\{r,41r,1681r\}\pmod {1723}.
\]
There are \(574\) such nonzero orbits.  A choice of \(14\) orbits is a
cyclic planar difference set if and only if it satisfies the following
exact-cover equations.

Let \(\Omega\) be the set of nonzero \(41\)-orbits.  For \(O,L\in\Omega\)
and unordered distinct \(O,P\in\Omega\), define
\[
 c_{O,L}
 =\frac{1}{3}\#\{(a,b)\in O^2:a-b\in L\},
\]
and
\[
 c_{O,P,L}
 =\frac{1}{3}\#\{(a,b)\in O\times P\cup P\times O:a-b\in L\}.
\]
These are integers: since \(L\) is nonzero, multiplication by \(41\)
acts freely on each counted set of ordered pairs, so the counted pairs
split into triples.
Then binary variables \(X_O\in\{0,1\}\) describe a normalized cyclic
planar difference set precisely when
\[
 \sum_{O\in\Omega}X_O=14
\]
and, for every \(L\in\Omega\),
\[
 \sum_{O\in\Omega}c_{O,L}X_O
 +\sum_{\{O,P\}\subset\Omega}c_{O,P,L}X_OX_P=1.
\]
If such a normalized set contains an affine copy of
\(S\in\{A,B\}\), then after scaling the common difference to \(1\) there
is some \(\tau\in\Z_{1723}\) such that
\[
 X_{[\tau+s]}=1\qquad(s\in S),
\]
with immediate infeasibility if any \(\tau+s\equiv0\pmod {1723}\).

For the representative translation \(\tau=1\), the forced point-orbits
are
\[
 A:\ [1],[2],[4],[12],
 \qquad
 B:\ [1],[2],[5],[12].
\]
In both cases the forced core is locally admissible: the internal and
cross difference-orbits listed below are \(44\) distinct orbits, so no
collision occurs before the remaining \(10\) orbits are chosen.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
The multiplier normalization follows from the multiplier theorem quoted
above with \(p=41\).  The integer \(1723\) is prime, and
\[
\begin{aligned}
 41^3&=68921\equiv1\pmod {1723},\\
 41&\not\equiv1\pmod {1723},\qquad
 41^2=1681\not\equiv1\pmod {1723}.
\end{aligned}
\]
Thus every nonzero orbit under multiplication by \(41\) has length \(3\).
The zero orbit has length \(1\), but a \(41\)-invariant difference set of
size \(42\) cannot contain it, since \(42-1=41\) is not divisible by
\(3\).  Hence every normalized difference set is a union of \(42/3=14\)
nonzero orbits, and
\[
 |\Omega|=\frac{1723-1}{3}=574.
\]

Let \(D=\bigcup_{O:X_O=1}O\).  The group-ring equation
\[
 DD^{(-1)}=41+\Z_{1723}
\]
is equivalent to saying that each nonzero residue occurs exactly once as
an ordered difference.  Since \(D\) is \(41\)-invariant, the number of
ordered differences landing in a fixed nonzero orbit \(L\) is constant
on the three elements of \(L\).  Therefore the coefficient sum over
\(L\) must be \(3\), or, after division by \(3\), must be \(1\).  The
terms with both entries in a selected orbit \(O\) contribute \(c_{O,L}\);
the ordered cross terms from two selected orbits \(O\ne P\) contribute
\(c_{O,P,L}\).  This gives exactly the displayed quadratic system.
Conversely, if the displayed system holds, then every nonzero orbit
receives total coefficient \(3\), and invariance forces coefficient
\(1\) on each of its three elements.  Hence \(D\) is a cyclic planar
difference set.

If \(D\) contains \(t+uS\) with \(u\in\Z_{1723}^\times\), then
\(u^{-1}D\) is still \(41\)-invariant and contains \(\tau+S\), where
\(\tau=u^{-1}t\).  This gives the forced constraints
\(X_{[\tau+s]}=1\), unless one of the forced points is \(0\), which is
impossible for a normalized \(41\)-invariant difference set.

\QFortyOneForcedCores
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}[Local \(q=41\) survivor scan]
\label{lem:q41-survivors}
Keep the notation of Lemma~\ref{lem:q41}.  For
\(S\in\{A,B\}\) and \(\tau\in\Z_{1723}\), let
\[
 \Lambda_S(\tau)=\{[\tau+s]:s\in S\},
\]
with repeated point-orbits identified.  Call \(\tau\) a local survivor
if no forced point \(\tau+s\) is congruent to \(0\), if every forced
internal difference list has size \(2\), if every forced cross
difference list for two distinct orbits in \(\Lambda_S(\tau)\) has size
\(6\), and if all of these forced difference-orbits are distinct.  The
script-verified local survivor counts are
\QFortyOneSurvivorTable
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
If a normalized \(41\)-invariant difference set contains \(\tau+S\),
then it must select every orbit in \(\Lambda_S(\tau)\).  A forced point
equal to \(0\) is impossible because the zero orbit is not present in
any normalized difference set.  For each selected orbit \(O\), the
internal difference-orbits with \(c_{O,L}>0\) already contribute to the
right-hand side of the exact-cover equation for \(L\).  For each
selected unordered pair \(O\ne P\), the cross difference-orbits with
\(c_{O,P,L}>0\) do the same.  Since every exact-cover equation in
Lemma~\ref{lem:q41} has right-hand side \(1\), a repeated forced
difference-orbit, or a forced internal or cross list smaller than the
generic sizes \(2\) and \(6\), is an immediate local contradiction.
Thus the displayed predicate is the necessary local test used in the
scan.  It is not asserted to be sufficient for completion to a
difference set.

