quotient by an invariant survivor set.
\end{proof}

\section{Discussion and open questions}

Theorem \ref{thm:singer} closes the Singer affine-orbit part of Niu's
evidence uniformly in \(q\).  Therefore any remaining obstruction to a
full extension theorem for \(A\) and \(B\) must come from cyclic planar
difference sets that are not forced into the Singer equivalence class.
Theorem \ref{thm:smallq} shows that this cannot happen below \(q=41\).

The first unresolved multiplier descent is the finite system in
Lemma \ref{lem:q41}.  For \(q=41\), every selected orbit contributes two
internal difference-orbits, and every selected unordered pair contributes
six cross difference-orbits.  Thus a solution with \(14\) selected
orbits must partition all \(574\) nonzero difference-orbits:
\[
 14\cdot 2+\binom{14}{2}\cdot 6=28+546=574.
\]
For the two representative forced cores at \(\tau=1\), \(44\) of these
orbits are already covered without collision.  The open computation is
to decide whether the remaining \(530\) difference-orbits can be covered
by ten more point-orbits.

More generally, after scaling an affine copy to common difference \(1\),
one must solve the same exact-cover problem with forced constraints
\[
 X_{[\tau]}=X_{[\tau+1]}=X_{[\tau+3]}=X_{[\tau+11]}=1
\]
for \(A\), or
\[
 X_{[\tau]}=X_{[\tau+1]}=X_{[\tau+4]}=X_{[\tau+11]}=1
\]
for \(B\).  A direct local forced-orbit scan at \(q=41\) leaves many
locally admissible translations, as recorded in
Lemma~\ref{lem:q41-survivors}.
That scan first identifies repeated forced point-orbits; in the generic
four-orbit case, it is exactly the \(44\)-forced-difference-orbit test
displayed in Lemma~\ref{lem:q41}.
Thus the frontier is not a one-line multiplier collision.  This note
does not claim a \(q=41\) certificate.  A certificate of infeasibility
for every surviving \(\tau\)-orbit would prove the \(q=41\) case, while
a feasible solution would produce a necessarily non-Singer cyclic planar
difference set of order \(41\) containing one of the patterns.  That
certificate-driven analysis is a separate verification problem from the
Singer trace-rank argument proved here.  The survivor counts are
therefore used only as a reproducible boundary check, not as a
standalone benchmark or as evidence of global infeasibility.

For larger prime powers the same distinction remains essential.  The
Singer affine obstruction is settled for all \(q\), but arbitrary cyclic
planar difference sets require either an external uniqueness theorem or
a non-Singer multiplier analysis.  Some later orders, such as \(49\)
and \(64\), are covered by classical uniqueness results of Bruck as
discussed by Huang and Schmidt \cite{Bruck,HuangSchmidt}.  At orders not
covered by existing classification, such as the next prime orders
\(53\) and \(71\), analogous orbit systems would require separate
order-specific arithmetic and certification, so they are not part of the
theorem chain of this note.

